## Why This Is Asked
Real systems require dynamic behavior; eviction is cross-cutting and benefits from a registry and strategy pattern. Hot-swapping policies tests state transfer, thread-safety, and cluster coherence.

## Key Concepts
- Strategy pattern for eviction
- Registry for runtime registration
- State serialization for hot-swapping
- Consistency in distributed caches

## Code Example
```typescript
interface EvictionPolicy<K, V> {
  onAccess(key: K, value: V, now: number): void
  evictCandidate(keys: K[]): K | null
  serialize(): string
  init(state: string): void
}

class PolicyRegistry<K, V> {
  private policies = new Map<string, () => EvictionPolicy<K, V>>()

  register(name: string, factory: () => EvictionPolicy<K, V>): void {
    this.policies.set(name, factory)
  }

  get(name: string): EvictionPolicy<K, V> {
    const factory = this.policies.get(name)
    if (!factory) throw new Error(`Policy '${name}' not found`)
    return factory()
  }

  list(): string[] {
    return Array.from(this.policies.keys())
  }
}

class LRUPolicy<K, V> implements EvictionPolicy<K, V> {
  private accessOrder = new Map<K, number>()

  onAccess(key: K, value: V, now: number): void {
    this.accessOrder.set(key, now)
  }

  evictCandidate(keys: K[]): K | null {
    let oldestKey: K | null = null
    let oldestTime = Infinity

    for (const key of keys) {
      const time = this.accessOrder.get(key) ?? 0
      if (time < oldestTime) {
        oldestTime = time
        oldestKey = key
      }
    }

    if (oldestKey) this.accessOrder.delete(oldestKey)
    return oldestKey
  }

  serialize(): string {
    return JSON.stringify(Object.fromEntries(this.accessOrder))
  }

  init(state: string): void {
    this.accessOrder = new Map(Object.entries(JSON.parse(state)))
  }
}

class DistributedCache<K, V> {
  private data = new Map<K, V>()
  private currentPolicy: EvictionPolicy<K, V>

  constructor(private registry: PolicyRegistry<K, V>, initialPolicy: string) {
    this.currentPolicy = this.registry.get(initialPolicy)
  }

  set(key: K, value: V): void {
    this.data.set(key, value)
    this.currentPolicy.onAccess(key, value, Date.now())

    if (this.isFull()) {
      const keys = Array.from(this.data.keys())
      const evictKey = this.currentPolicy.evictCandidate(keys)
      if (evictKey) this.data.delete(evictKey)
    }
  }

  switchPolicy(newPolicyName: string): void {
    const oldState = this.currentPolicy.serialize()
    this.currentPolicy = this.registry.get(newPolicyName)
    this.currentPolicy.init(oldState)
  }

  private isFull(): boolean { return false /* size check */ }
}
```

## Trade-offs for Cluster Coherence

**State Synchronization**: Serialized policy state must be distributed across nodes, adding network overhead during policy switches.

**Consistency Windows**: During hot-swaps, nodes may operate with different policies temporarily, requiring version negotiation.

**Performance Impact**: Registry lookups and serialization add microsecond-level overhead to critical cache operations.

**Complexity vs Flexibility**: The registry pattern increases code complexity but enables A/B testing and adaptive policies.

